                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17730626-59-off337 t17730626-59-crimeloc339"></join>. A gentleman standing at his door saw the prisoner take it out of my pocket; he stopped him and came and informed me of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17730626-59-person662">
                  John
                   Hunt
               <interp inst="t17730626-59-person662" type="surname" value="Hunt"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730626-59-person662" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17730626-59-person662" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Standing at my own door the 19th of May, I saw the prisoner take the handkerchief out of Mr. Nicholson's pocket; I ran from my own door and detected him with it in his hand; as soon as I laid hold of him he dropt it; I gave it to Mr. Nicholson. (The handkerchief produced and deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>A gentleman laid hold of me, and said I had his handkerchief; I never saw any thing of it.</p>
               <p>For the Prisoner.</p>
               <p>- Preston. He always bore a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177306260044"></xptr>Hyam Lazarus, the prisoner's father. I carry milk in the morning, and make chocolate in the afternoon; he always behaved very well.</p>


